Read (and filter) county features into an sf dataframe and plot

In this exercise, we will be exploring stream gage height data in Nebraska corresponding to floods occurring there in 2019. First, we will import from the US Counties shapefile we’ve used in lab lessons, filtering it this time for just Nebraska counties. Nebraska’s state FIPS code is 31 (as North Carolina’s was 37).

  1. Read the cb_2018_us_county_20m.shp shapefile into an sf dataframe, filtering records for Nebraska counties (State FIPS = 31)
  2. Reveal the dataset’s coordinate reference system
  3. Plot the records as a map (using mapview or ggplot)
#3. Read in Counties shapefile into an sf dataframe, filtering for just NE counties
ne_counties <- st_read('./Data/Spatial/cb_2018_us_county_20m.shp') %>%
  filter(STATEFP == 31)

  1. What is the EPSG code of the Counties dataset? Is this a geographic or a projected coordinate reference system? (Or, does this CRS use angular or planar coordinate units?) To what datum is this CRS associated? (Tip: look the EPSG code on https://spatialreference.org)

ANSWER:

The CRS for this dataset is NAD83, and the EPSG code for this dataset is 4269. It is associated to the North American Datum 1983, based on the Geodetic Reference System (GRS) 1980 ellipsoid. This CRS is a geographic coordinate reference system.

Read in gage locations csv as a dataframe, then display the column names it contains

Next we’ll read in some USGS/NWIS gage location data added to the Data/Raw folder. These are in the NWIS_SiteInfo_NE_RAW.csv file.(See NWIS_SiteInfo_NE_RAW.README.txt for more info on this dataset.)

  1. Read the NWIS_SiteInfo_NE_RAW.csv file into a standard dataframe.

  2. Display the column names of this dataset.

#7. Read in gage locations csv as a dataframe
gages <- read.csv("./Data/Raw/NWIS_SiteInfo_NE_RAW.csv", colClasses = c('site_no' = 'factor'), stringsAsFactors = TRUE)

#8. Reveal the names of the columns
colnames(gages)
## [1] "site_no"            "station_nm"         "site_tp_cd"        
## [4] "dec_lat_va"         "dec_long_va"        "coord_acy_cd"      
## [7] "dec_coord_datum_cd"
  1. What columns in the dataset contain the x and y coordinate values, respectively?

ANSWER:

The x coordinates come from the longitude values, located in the “dec_long_va” column. The y coordinates come from the latitude values, located in the “dec_lat_va” column.

Convert the dataframe to a spatial features (“sf”) dataframe

  1. Convert the dataframe to an sf dataframe.
  • Note: These data use the same coordinate reference system as the counties dataset
  1. Display the column names of the resulting sf dataframe
#10. Convert to an sf object
gages_spatial <- gages %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c('dec_long_va','dec_lat_va'),
           crs=4269)

#11. Re-examine the column names
colnames(gages_spatial)
## [1] "site_no"            "station_nm"         "site_tp_cd"        
## [4] "coord_acy_cd"       "dec_coord_datum_cd" "geometry"
  1. What new field(s) appear in the sf dataframe created? What field(s), if any, disappeared?

ANSWER:

The original fields in the regular dataframe were “site_no”, “station_nm”, “site_tp_cd”, “dec_lat_va”, “dec_long_va”, “coord_acy_cd”, and “dec_coord_datum_cd”. In the new spatial dataframe, the two columns with the lat/long coordinates disappeared, and were replaced by a singular column called “geometry”. This column contained point data for each row, along with each point’s associated coordinates that were synthesized from the original lat/long columns.

Read in the gage height data and join the site location data to it.

Lastly, we want to attach some gage height data to our site locations. I’ve constructed a csv file listing many of the Nebraska gage sites, by station name and site number along with stream gage heights (in meters) recorded during the recent flood event. This file is titled NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv and is found in the Data/Raw folder.

  1. Read in and wrangle the NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv dataset:
  • Be sure the site_no column is read in as a factor
  • Group by site_no and station_nm, computing the mean gage_ht across groups values
  1. Show the column names .
  2. Join our site information (already imported above) to these gage height data.
  • The site_no and station_nm can both/either serve as joining attributes.
  • Construct this join so that the result only includes spatial features where both tables have data.
  1. Show the column names in this resulting spatial features object
  2. Show the dimensions of the resulting joined dataframe
#14. Read the site flow data into a data frame
mean_gage_ht <- read.csv("./Data/Raw/NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv",
  colClasses = c('site_no' = 'factor')) %>%  
  group_by(site_no, station_nm) %>% 
  summarize(MeanGageHT = mean(gage_ht))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'site_no'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
#15. Show the column names
colnames(mean_gage_ht)
## [1] "site_no"    "station_nm" "MeanGageHT"
#16. Join the flow data to our NWIS gage location spatial dataframe
gage_flow_data <- left_join(gages_spatial, mean_gage_ht) %>% na.omit()
## Joining, by = c("site_no", "station_nm")
#17. Show the column names of the joined dataset
colnames(gage_flow_data)
## [1] "site_no"            "station_nm"         "site_tp_cd"        
## [4] "coord_acy_cd"       "dec_coord_datum_cd" "MeanGageHT"        
## [7] "geometry"
#18. Show the dimensions of this joined dataset
dim(gage_flow_data) #118 rows, 7 columns
## [1] 118   7

Map the pattern of gage height data

Now we can examine where the flooding appears most acute by visualizing gage heights spatially. 19. Plot the gage sites on top of counties (using mapview, ggplot, or leaflet) * Show the magnitude of gage height by color, shape, other visualization technique.

#Map the points, sized by gage height

#by color, in ggplot
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = ne_counties, fill = 'white', color = 'black') +
  geom_sf(data=gage_flow_data, aes(color = MeanGageHT, geometry = geometry),alpha=.8) +
  scale_color_gradient(low="lightpink",high="darkred") +
  labs(title = "Flooding Severity in Nebraska",
       subtitle = "Ana Bishop",
       color = "Mean Gage Height") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

#by size, in ggplot
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = ne_counties, fill = 'white', color = 'black') +
  geom_sf(data=gage_flow_data, aes(size = MeanGageHT, geometry = geometry), alpha=.3, color = "darkgreen") +
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(1, 7)) +
  labs(title = "Flooding Severity in Nebraska",
       subtitle = "Ana Bishop",
       size = "Mean Gage Height") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

#by size, in leaflet
ne_counties_wgs84 <- st_transform(ne_counties, c=4326)
gage_flow_data_wgs84 <- st_transform(gage_flow_data, c=4326)

leaflet() %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.TonerHybrid) %>% 
  addPolygons(data = ne_counties_wgs84,weight=0.2,color = "white") %>% 
  addCircleMarkers(data=gage_flow_data_wgs84,
                   radius=(~MeanGageHT*2),
                   stroke = FALSE, 
                   fillOpacity = 0.3,
                   popup = ~as.character(`MeanGageHT`))

SPATIAL ANALYSIS

Up next we will do some spatial analysis with our data. To prepare for this, we should transform our data into a projected coordinate system. We’ll choose UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).

Transform the counties and gage site datasets to UTM Zone 14N

  1. Transform the counties and gage sf datasets to UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).
  2. Using mapview or ggplot, plot the data so that each can be seen as different colors
#20 Transform the counties and gage location datasets to UTM Zone 14
ne_counties_utm <- st_transform(ne_counties, c=32614)
gage_flow_data_utm <- st_transform(gage_flow_data, c=32614)

Select the gages falling within a given county

Now let’s zoom into a particular county and examine the gages located there. 22. Select Douglas county from your projected county sf dataframe 23. Select the gage sites falling within that county * Use either matrix subsetting or tidy filtering 24. Create a plot showing: * all Nebraska counties, * the selected county, * and the gage sites in that county

#22 Select the county
douglas_county <- ne_counties_utm %>% filter(NAME == "Douglas")

#23 Select gages within the selected county
intersecting_gages <- gage_flow_data_utm %>% 
  st_filter(douglas_county, .pred = st_intersects)

#24 Plot
#in ggplot:
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = ne_counties_utm, fill = 'white', color = 'black') +
  geom_sf(data = douglas_county, fill = "lightgray") +
  geom_sf(data = intersecting_gages, color = 'black', alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "NWIS Gage Locations in Douglas County, Nebraska",
       subtitle = "Ana Bishop") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

#in mapview:
mapview(ne_counties_utm, 
            col.regions = 'yellow', 
            alpha.regions = 0.2,
            map.types = "CartoDB.Positron",
            legend = FALSE) +
  mapview(douglas_county, 
          col.regions = "orange",
          alpha.regions = 0.7) +

          col.regions = "black",
